lead_paragraph: 9:15 A.M. (IFC) IGBY GOES DOWN (2002) Kieran Culkin portrays Igby, a 17-year-old military school runaway who camps out in a New York loft as he rebels against his preppy older brother (Ryan Phillippe) and high-strung mother (Susan Sarandon), in this sarcastic comedy written and directed by Burt Steers. Amanda Peet, above with Mr. Culkin, is the heroin-addicted choreographer and trophy girlfriend of Igby’s wealthy godfather and benefactor (Jeff Goldblum) with whom Igby finds solace; Bill Pullman is Igby’s father, in a mental hospital after a schizophrenic breakdown. “Even though the movie drifts uneasily between satire and realism, and its visions of military school and bohemia feel secondhand, it maintains a ruthless emotional honesty,” Stephen Holden wrote in The New York Times. “Ultimately, it gets at something that no other recent American movie has captured quite so acutely: a resentful, lurking disappointment in the good life.”

abstract: At 14, I tried to run away. But millions of molting cicadas, and a mother who loved me, came between me and my freedom.
snippet: At 14, I tried to run away. But millions of molting cicadas, and a mother who loved me, came between me and my freedom.
lead_paragraph: I was 14 and desolate, living in a place so unlike the vibrant home I’d left behind that I named it “Dead City.” Determined to return to civilization, I planned to hitchhike to O’Hare Airport and buy a ticket back to New York. There was just one hurdle. Outside my grandmother’s suburban front door was a plague of cicadas.

abstract: Marijuana is becoming increasingly legal. Cheryl Shuman wants to make it increasingly glamorous.
snippet: Marijuana is becoming increasingly legal. Cheryl Shuman wants to make it increasingly glamorous.
lead_paragraph: Cheryl Shuman, founder of the Beverly Hills Cannabis Club, arrived at the Perennial Holistic Wellness Center, an upmarket medical-marijuana dispensary in Los Angeles, in a red 2010 Ferrari California, a gift, she said, from a friend. She had come to get supplies for a “mansion party” that she was hosting the following evening, one of the semiregular events she organizes with her daughter, Aimee, to promote their marijuana enterprises. Shuman, a tall 54-year-old blonde with the unflagging cheer of someone accustomed to being noticed, handed the keys to Perennial’s valets with a Mae West-inflected “Careful, boys.” She headed inside to present her state-issued Medical Marijuana Identification Card.

abstract: Ms. Boxer, a California Democrat who has served in the Senate since 1993, says in a video interview with a grandson, “I want to come home to the state that I love.”
snippet: Ms. Boxer, a California Democrat who has served in the Senate since 1993, says in a video interview with a grandson, “I want to come home to the state that I love.”
lead_paragraph: LOS ANGELES — Senator Barbara Boxer announced Thursday that she would not seek re-election as senator from California, ending a 30-year career in Congress and breaking a generational logjam in a state where the three top political officeholders are older than 70.
headline_main: Boxer Says She Won’t Seek Re-election to Senate in California in 2016
headline_print_headline: Boxer Says She Won’t Seek Re-election to Senate in California in 2016

abstract: The company’s new compact crossover is a commendable effort that shares an engine with the Ford Mustang.
snippet: The company’s new compact crossover is a commendable effort that shares an engine with the Ford Mustang.
lead_paragraph: A few years back, the future looked hazy for Lincoln. Ford’s luxury division had killed its best-known model, the Town Car. The MKZ looked like a gussied-up Fusion, the MKX was based on the Edge.
headline_main: Video Review: The Lincoln MKC Is the Right Vehicle at the Right Time
headline_print_headline: Lincoln MKC: Right Vehicle at the Right Time

abstract: Tom Eve, 63, has not lost his boyish enthusiasm for fire trucks, custom building models for clients who request replicas of pumpers and ladder trucks.
snippet: Tom Eve, 63, has not lost his boyish enthusiasm for fire trucks, custom building models for clients who request replicas of pumpers and ladder trucks.
lead_paragraph: Tom Eve, 63, still remembers the day in 1958 that the firehouse on his South Bronx block got its new pumper: a gleaming new Mack whose cab could fit five firefighters.
